u]\:03ac\[Mu]\[CurlyEpsilon]\[Iota]\[FinalSigma]. The KJV\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]nor principalities, nor powers, nor things present...\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] reflects the TR/Byzantine tendency to pair \:1f00\[Rho]\[Chi]\[Alpha]\:03af and \[Delta]\[Upsilon]\[Nu]\:03ac\[Mu]\[CurlyEpsilon]\[Iota]\[FinalSigma], familiar from Pauline catalogues of cosmic authorities. The SBLGNT/NA order, \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]rulers ... things present ... things to come ... powers,\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] is less tidy and therefore plausibly prior. Lexically, \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]principalities\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] for \:1f00\[Rho]\[Chi]\[Alpha]\:03af is defensible in early modern English, where the word could denote ruling authorities or angelic orders, but it now often suggests geographical states; \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]rulers\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] better signals the active, personal/cosmic force implied by BDAG s.v. \:1f00\[Rho]\[Chi]\:03ae. Conversely, \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]powers\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] remains a good rendering of \[Delta]\[Upsilon]\[Nu]\:03ac\[Mu]\[CurlyEpsilon]\[Iota]\[FinalSigma], though in Paul it can denote supra-human forces rather than abstract capacities."|>, "raw" -> "{\n  \"primary_nuance\": \"The KJV follows the Textus Receptus/Byzantine order by placing \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]powers\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] immediately after \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]principalities,\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] whereas the SBLGNT separates \[Delta]\[Upsilon]\[Nu]\:03ac\[Mu]\[CurlyEpsilon]\[Iota]\[FinalSigma] and leaves it after \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]things to come.\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]\",\n  \"category\": \"textual-variant\",\n  \"key_term\": \"\[Delta]\:03cd\[Nu]\[Alpha]\[Mu]\[Iota]\[FinalSigma]\",\n  \"english_drift\": \"\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]principalities\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]: in KJV usage, ruling authorities or high angelic orders; in modern English, chiefly territories ruled by a prince.\",\n  \"textual_note\": \"SBLGNT/NA28 reads \[Omi